When we get closer to the late May/early June pride discourse, I'll write a longer thread about why "no kink at pride" is actually just a slippery slope argument writ large, but for now, I want y'all to understand that queer people don't need anyone's permission to exist.

Queerness is that part of us that screams for liberation, for change, for love and jouissance. It is never satisfied with the status quo, nor should it be. It pushes and needles and dreams. 

Queerness cannot be contained, and that frightens people.

You knew I had to talk about Baedan at least once during this thread, so here's a quote I've considered getting tattooed somewhere on my body at least once:

"Queerness can never define an identity, it can only ever disrupt one."

I get it. I get that it's a trauma response. I get that it's holding on to your identity, kicking and screaming, terrified that someone else will invalidate you and take it away from you. 

These feelings are valid, but the reactions are absolutely harmful.

In a very real way, "no kink at pride" is about reducing LGBTQIA+ down to LG.

Same with "queer is a slur". Ambiguity is dangerous. Atomize everyone into little boxes. Allow no room for fluidity and adaptation and exploration.

Moral panics always glom onto very real traumatic experiences and twist them into something totally unrecognizable.

"No kink at pride" isn't about public sex. It's about getting rid of people who don't conform to a very cis definition of not-straight.

To me, "no kink at pride" is particularly insidious because the reason given is always "think of the children!!!"

I am a survivor of both grooming and relationship abuse, and people who use that line pretend like they want to protect me. They don't.

This is also an unfriendly reminder that "queer is a slur" and "no kink at pride" are both TERF/SWERF 📀🐎 inroads to fetishizing and demonizing anyone who doesn't fit into neat, cis, monosexual, monogamous categories.

Because I'm sure someone with Twitter brain will see this: I'm not saying queer people should be allowed to be abusive, bigoted, etc. without consequence.

I'm saying that queer people should be allowed to be happy and wear what they like without peers going "BUT THE CHILDREN"

We're allowed to be messy.

We're allowed to fuck up.

We shouldn't have to pass a vibe check, a background check, and a jury ruling of our peers to be able to go outside.

That's some fucking carceral horseshit.

I'm seeing the "queer people need to be more CAREFUL about how they express themselves" discourse beginning earlier in some spaces this year, so this is your reminder that queer people don't need to be role models to exist in public spaces.

We should absolutely keep ramping up the queer, disabled, Mad, POC, etc content.

We should absolutely keep ramping up the ways we talk about safety, risk mitigation, and exploration in good faith. 

We can do that without appending "and fuck you reader" to every paragraph. 14/14

101 writing is awesome and absolutely has its place. 

Assuming our audience are all straight cis white men who have no ability to talk to their straight cis white players and don't care about them is something I'd like to see phased out. 13/

actually suggested a path to healing, though in a bit of a tongue in cheek way. 

I still think that's fine within the context of this thread. 

What I struggle with is constantly presenting marginalized and safety content as though the audience hasn't considered it before. 12/

I admit that I did write "If you're a Nazi or any flavor of alt-right, put down this book and call a friend to figure out where you went so wrong" in the V5 Appendix For Considerate Play. 

And that was defensive, but it was a) in light of actual Nazis in the scene and b) 11/

We're so used to defending ourselves in our personal lives, getting swept up in TTRPG 📀🐴 and looking for reasons to dunk on creators for shitty takes that we don't see... the people we're writing for any more?

And that fucking sucks! 10/

audience!

(I'm only using the most obvious example here. I have no beef with Thirsty Sword Lesbians.) 9/

I'm queer and I've seen the same thing. "If you don't like queer people you can't play this game"

I mean, I support that. 100%. But think about that for a second. Think about who's picking up your book. 

It's extremely unlikely Thirsty Sword Lesbians is going to a homophobic 8/

You are actively pitting yourself against the audience, who don't know what's good for them and those around them. 

I've seen games whose safety sections start with "If you don't like safety rules? Fuck you, you suck" and variations on the same. 7/

Writing defensively doesn't call in your readers who agree with you, it specifically draws a line between you and your readers with you as "us" and your readers, no matter who they are, as "them".

This can be great in certain styles of writing, but in TTRPGS/LARPS? 6/

your readers know that. You want to scream to the world that you're present and doing the thing regardless of how much it's tried to keep you down. 

That's awesome! But it glosses over the fact that maybe your readers are marginalized and/or care about safety ALREADY. 5/

I add this note because the Twitter brain is an anxiety response. I don't want to be misinterpreted. 

I suspect that when you write safety content or content about marginalized communities, you don't either! You want to present like you're qualified to write it, and 4/

Twitter brain note: this thread is NOT ABOUT telling you not to write queer/marginalized content or risk mitigation/safety content. Don't come here trying that, please. This is about different approaches to writing it. 3/
